properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A total of 25 to 40 millimetres of rain is expected by Friday evening. A low pressure system is bringing rain, at times heavy, over Quebec, which will continue on Friday. Total rainfall amounts approaching 50 millimetres are possible locally. Since spring freshet has not ended in many areas, flooding is possible in the most vulnerable areas. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief heavy downpours possible this afternoon. Although the majority of heavy rainfall has moved out of the area, there could still be shower or thunderstorm development this afternoon. Brief heavy downpours from these showers or thunderstorms could occur, giving additional amounts of 10 to 15 mm. The ground, already near saturation, has a lessened ability to absorb further rainfall. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry District Office. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-05-11T01:17:13-00:00

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Higher pressure over the Northwest Territories combined with low pressure over the Yukon will generate strong winds through the Richardson Mountains today. Winds at Rock River are forecast to rise to easterly 80 gusting to 100 km/h this afternoon and then diminish to light late this evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
